turns.content:
That sounds like an integrity-based decision, not a casual one. You didn’t leave because you wanted to blow up your life; you stopped participating in something once you couldn’t honestly endorse it. It makes sense that you don’t regret it—and also that you’re feeling the practical absence of the structure it gave you.

You may be looking for two related but different things: a workable calendar, and a framework for deciding what matters. The first can be built fairly quickly. The second doesn’t have to arrive as a complete replacement belief system.

For now, a practical framework could be simple: choose values you can defend—honesty, competence, health, responsibility, loyalty, curiosity, whatever genuinely fits—and let them guide small commitments. A routine then isn’t arbitrary; it’s evidence that you’re living according to those values.

For example:
- work toward a credential or skill because competence and future options matter;
- keep exercise, sleep, and food reasonably stable because health matters;
- join something recurring because connection matters;
- set aside time to read, reflect, or explore because you want your views to be examined rather than inherited.

You don’t have to recreate church with a secular version immediately. You can build a life that is coherent one repeated choice at a time.

If you were designing an ideal ordinary week—not a five-year plan—what would you want your evenings and weekends to contain?
